  "prompt": "Why hollow shaft can transmit more torque than solid shaft?",
  "response": "A hollow shaft can transmit more torque than a solid shaft of the same outer diameter due to several key factors:\n\n1. Material Distribution\n- Hollow shaft concentrates more material near the outer diameter\n- Larger radius of material from the center increases moment of inertia\n- Better stress distribution across the cross-section\n\n2. Weight Reduction\n- Lower weight compared to solid shaft\n- Reduced mass while maintaining similar strength\n- Improved power-to-weight ratio\n\n3. Mechanical Advantage\n- Greater radius provides larger lever arm\n- Enhanced torque transmission capability\n- More efficient power transfer\n\n4. Stress Characteristics\n- Reduced internal stresses\n- Lower stress concentration at the center\n- Better resistance to torsional deformation\n\n5. Moment of Inertia\n- Higher polar moment of inertia\n- Improved torsional stiffness\n- Better resistance to twisting\n\n6. Material Savings\n- Less material required\n- Cost-effective manufacturing\n- Economic design approach\n\n7. Thermal Performance\n- Better heat dissipation\n- Reduced thermal stress\n- Improved overall mechanical reliability\n\nThese advantages make hollow shafts preferred in many mechanical and engineering applications requiring efficient torque transmission.",
